    The crash is caused by an out-of-bounds read in parse_string() when         
    parsing an unterminated JSON string.                                        
                                                                                
    Input:                                                                      
                                                                                
                                                                                
     "abc                                                                       
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This starts a JSON string with ", but never closes it. The parser should    
    reject the input cleanly. Instead, parse_string() scans forward looking     
    for the closing quote without checking that it is still inside the input    
    buffer before dereferencing the pointer.                                    
                                                                                
    The defective code is here:                                                 
                                                                                
                                                                                
     while (*input_end != '\"')                                                 
     {                                                                          
         /* is escape sequence */                                               
         if (input_end[0] == '\\')                                              
         {                                                                      
             if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >=             
     input_buffer->length)                                                      
             {                                                                  
                 /* prevent buffer overflow when last input character is a      
     backslash */                                                               
                 goto fail;                                                     
             }                                                                  
             skipped_bytes++;                                                   
             input_end++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >=                        
     input_buffer->length) || (*input_end != '\"'))                             
     {                                                                          
         goto fail; /* string ended unexpectedly */                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    The bounds check happens after the loop, but the loop condition itself      
    already dereferences *input_end. If no closing quote exists, input_end      
    advances past the end of the allocated buffer and the next loop condition   
    reads one byte out of bounds.                                               
                                                                                
    Step-by-step state:                                                         
                                                                                
     1 bench_driver.c reads the input:                                          
                                                                                
        size_t n = fread(tmp, 1, sizeof(tmp), stdin);                           
        char *buf = malloc(n + 1);                                              
        memcpy(buf, tmp, n);                                                    
        buf[n] = '\0';                                                          
                                                                                
       For input "abc, n == 4.                                                  
       The heap allocation has 5 bytes:                                         
                                                                                
        index:  0    1    2    3    4                                           
        byte:   "    a    b    c   \0                                           
                                                                                
     2 main() calls:                                                            
                                                                                
        cJSON_ParseWithOpts(buf, &err, 0);                                      
                                                                                
     3 cJSON_ParseWithOpts() computes:                                          
                                                                                
        buffer_length = strlen(value) + sizeof("");                             
                                                                                
       Since strlen("\"abc") == 4 and sizeof("") == 1, buffer_length == 5.      
       So the parser buffer covers the bytes:                                   
                                                                                
        "abc\0                                                                  
                                                                                
     4 parse_value() sees the first byte is ", so it calls:                     
                                                                                
        parse_string(item, input_buffer);                                       
                                                                                
     5 In parse_string():                                                       
                                                                                
        const unsigned char *input_pointer = buffer_at_offset(input_buffer) +   
        1;                                                                      
        const unsigned char *input_end = buffer_at_offset(input_buffer) + 1;    
                                                                                
       Since buffer_at_offset(input_buffer) points at the opening quote, both   
       input_pointer and input_end initially point at the a.                    
     6 The loop searches for the terminating quote:                             
                                                                                
        while (*input_end != '\"')                                              
                                                                                
       It visits:                                                               
                                                                                
        input_end -> 'a'   not quote, increment                                 
        input_end -> 'b'   not quote, increment                                 
        input_end -> 'c'   not quote, increment                                 
        input_end -> '\0'  not quote, increment                                 
        input_end -> one past allocation                                        
                                                                                
     7 The next evaluation of:                                                  
                                                                                
        *input_end                                                              
                                                                                
       reads one byte past the heap allocation. AddressSanitizer reports this   
       as a heap buffer overflow.                                               
                                                                                
    The root cause is not the malformed input itself. Malformed JSON should     
    produce a parse failure. The root cause is that parse_string()              
    dereferences input_end before proving that input_end is still within        
    input_buffer->length.                                                       
                                                                                
    A minimal local fix is to add a bounds check to the loop condition before   
    dereferencing input_end:                                                    
                                                                                
                                                                                
     while (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) <                      
     input_buffer->length) &&                                                   
            (*input_end != '\"'))                                               
     {                                                                          
         /* is escape sequence */                                               
         if (input_end[0] == '\\')                                              
         {                                                                      
             if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >=             
     input_buffer->length)                                                      
             {                                                                  
                 /* prevent buffer overflow when last input character is a      
     backslash */                                                               
                 goto fail;                                                     
             }                                                                  
             skipped_bytes++;                                                   
             input_end++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >=                        
     input_buffer->length) ||                                                   
         (*input_end != '\"'))                                                  
     {                                                                          
         goto fail; /* string ended unexpectedly */                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Because || short-circuits, the post-loop check remains safe: if input_end   
    is out of range, *input_end is not evaluated.                               
                                                                                
    A cleaner version avoids repeating the pointer arithmetic inline:           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     while ((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) <                       
     input_buffer->length)                                                      
     {                                                                          
         if (*input_end == '\"')                                                
         {                                                                      
             break;                                                             
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         if (*input_end == '\\')                                                
         {                                                                      
             if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >=             
     input_buffer->length)                                                      
             {                                                                  
                 goto fail;                                                     
             }                                                                  
                                                                                
             skipped_bytes++;                                                   
             input_end++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >=                        
     input_buffer->length) ||                                                   
         (*input_end != '\"'))                                                  
     {                                                                          
         goto fail; /* string ended unexpectedly */                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    That fixes the immediate heap overflow.                                     
                                                                                
    A more thorough root-cause fix would be to make all string scanning in      
    parse_string() consistently length-based instead of sentinel-based. JSON    
    strings are not C strings; they are ranges inside a parse buffer. The       
    parser should never rely on eventually finding either " or '\0'. Every      
    read from input_pointer, input_end, or escape lookahead positions should    
    be guarded by input_buffer->length.                                         
                                                                                
    For example, the first scan can be structured as:                           
                                                                                
                                                                                
     const unsigned char * const buffer_end =                                   
         input_buffer->content + input_buffer->length;                          
                                                                                
     while (input_end < buffer_end)                                             
     {                                                                          
         if (*input_end == '\"')                                                
         {                                                                      
             break;                                                             
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         if (*input_end == '\\')                                                
         {                                                                      
             if ((input_end + 1) >= buffer_end)                                 
             {                                                                  
                 goto fail;                                                     
             }                                                                  
                                                                                
             skipped_bytes++;                                                   
             input_end++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
                                                                                
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     if ((input_end >= buffer_end) || (*input_end != '\"'))                     
     {                                                                          
         goto fail;                                                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    This makes the parser’s invariant explicit: input_end may only be           
    dereferenced while input_end < buffer_end.                                  
                                                                                
    The benchmark driver is mostly doing the right thing by allocating n + 1    
    and NUL-terminating the input. However, since it already knows the exact    
    number of bytes read, it would be preferable for a fuzzing or benchmark     
    driver to call the length-aware API directly:                               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cJSON *item = cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts(buf, n, &err, 0);                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    or, if the parser expects the terminating NUL to be included:               
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cJSON *item = cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts(buf, n + 1, &err, 0);              
                                                                                
                                                                                
    But that does not replace the parser fix. Even with the length-aware API,   
    parse_string() must not read past input_buffer->length.                     
                                                                                
    Recommendation                                                              
                                                                                
    Fix parse_string() so the search for the closing quote checks the           
    parse-buffer bounds before dereferencing input_end:                         
                                                                                
                                                                                
     while (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) <                      
     input_buffer->length) &&                                                   
            (*input_end != '\"'))                                               
     {                                                                          
         if (input_end[0] == '\\')                                              
         {                                                                      
             if ((size_t)(input_end + 1 - input_buffer->content) >=             
     input_buffer->length)                                                      
             {                                                                  
                 goto fail;                                                     
             }                                                                  
             skipped_bytes++;                                                   
             input_end++;                                                       
         }                                                                      
         input_end++;                                                           
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
     if (((size_t)(input_end - input_buffer->content) >=                        
     input_buffer->length) ||                                                   
         (*input_end != '\"'))                                                  
     {                                                                          
         goto fail;                                                             
     }                                                                          
                                                                                
                                                                                
    Additionally, consider changing the driver to use the length-aware API:     
                                                                                
                                                                                
     cJSON *item = cJSON_ParseWithLengthOpts(buf, n, &err, 0);                  
                                                                                
                                                                                
    but the parser-side bounds check is the actual required fix.                
                                                                                
